qx|HOW,Howard's Comments|
HT|E|CS|1|CP|4|AT|^-
{          Howard's Comments          }
^-|CS||CP||fp||AT|^B@2^Y@3I|FP||AT| have two notes on the material in this chapter. |
pg| ***** 104 ***** |


FP||cp|8|at|
^B@2^Y@3A. |FP||cp||at|I support Watson's statement that drawing trumps as soon as possible is important, because you do not want to let the defenders trump your winners with their low trumps. So, your first order of business when planning out the play of a hand is to decide if you can draw trumps immediately. You should do so, unless there is a good reason not to. However, on more hands than not, drawing trumps (or at least drawing all of the opponents trump), must be delayed. Here are the most common reasons:|
PG| ***** 105 ***** |


AT|

1) The most common reason to not draw trumps is that you need to use some of dummy's trumps to ruff out losers. If you draw all the opponents' trumps, dummy might not have any trump cards left to ruff out those losers. In that case, you need to exhaust the short suit in dummy first, before drawing trumps.|
PG| ***** 106 ***** |


AT|

2) The opponents can make you exhaust all your trumps before you establish your side suit winners. This is known as "losing control." If the opponents are able to exhaust you of all of your trumps, should they get back in the lead you will be effectively playing a no trump contract at that point. The opponents can cash the little cards in their long side suits, because you are no longer able to trump them. Although this can occur on any hand, the most common time this occurs is when you have 4 trumps in each hand. |
PG| ***** 107 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|E|CS|1|CP|4|AT|^-
{          Howard's Comments          }
^-|CS||CP||fp||AT|^B@2^Y@3I|FP||AT|t takes at least 3 rounds to draw all of the opponents' trump (since the best you can hope for is a 3-2 split). If you have already ruffed a loser in one of the hands, you will only have one remaining trump after drawing trumps (since the hand in which you ruffed now only has 3 trumps remaining). Therefore, if you have to lose the lead after drawing trumps, the opponents might be able to make you ruff with your only remaining trump. If you then lose the lead again, you will have no more trump left to protect against small cards that have been established in the opponents long suits. To remedy this situation, you might have to knock out the opponents' high cards in a suit before drawing trumps.|
PG| ***** 108 ***** |


AT|

By the way, this illustrates an important point about choice of contracts. In general, it is better to play in a 4-4 fit than a 5-3 fit. This is because you can use the 5 card suit to pitch losers from the other hand, and trump those losers. However, if you are in danger of losing control, then the presence of a 5th trump in one hand gives you an extra measure of protection. This should be given serious consideration when choosing your contract, particularly if you have a singleton or void in a side suit; in that case, having a long trump suit can be crucial in preventing you from losing control.|
PG| ***** 109 ***** |


AT|

3) You need the trump suit for entries to play other suits appropriately.|
PG| ***** 110 ***** |


